# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: recursion-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] In mathematical logic, the **arithmetical hierarchy**, **arithmetic hierarchy** or **Kleene–Mostowski hierarchy** (after mathematicians Stephen Cole Kleene and Andrzej Mostowski) classifies certain sets based on the complexity of formulas that define them.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Any set that receives a classification is called **arithmetical**.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The arithmetical hierarchy was invented independently by Kleene (1943) and Mostowski (1946).
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The arithmetical hierarchy is important in computability theory, effective descriptive set theory, and the study of formal theories such as Peano arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The Tarski–Kuratowski algorithm provides an easy way to get an upper bound on the classifications assigned to a formula and the set it defines.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The hyperarithmetical hierarchy and the analytical hierarchy extend the arithmetical hierarchy to classify additional formulas and sets.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The arithmetical hierarchy assigns classifications to the formulas in the language of first-order arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The classifications are denoted $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ for natural numbers *n* (including 0).
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The Greek letters here are lightface symbols, which indicates that the formulas do not contain set parameters.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] If a formula $\phi$ is logically equivalent to a formula having no unbounded quantifiers, i.e. in which all quantifiers are bounded quantifiers then $\phi$ is assigned the classifications $\Sigma _{0}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{0}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Because every first-order formula has a prenex normal form, every formula is assigned at least one classification.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Because redundant quantifiers can be added to any formula, once a formula is assigned the classification $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ or $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ it will be assigned the classifications $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{m}^{0}$ for every *m* > *n*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The only relevant classification assigned to a formula is thus the one with the least *n*; all the other classifications can be determined from it.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] where ${\underline {n}}$ is the numeral in the language of arithmetic corresponding to n .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A set is definable in first-order arithmetic if it is defined by some formula in the language of Peano arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Each set *X* of natural numbers that is definable in first-order arithmetic is assigned classifications of the form $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ , $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ , and $\Delta _{n}^{0}$ , where n is a natural number, as follows.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] If *X* is definable by a $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ formula then *X* is assigned the classification $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] If *X* is definable by a $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ formula then *X* is assigned the classification $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] If *X* is both $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ then X is assigned the additional classification $\Delta _{n}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] It rarely makes sense to speak of $\Delta _{n}^{0}$ *formulas*; the first quantifier of a formula is either existential or universal.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] So a $\Delta _{n}^{0}$ set is not necessarily defined by a $\Delta _{n}^{0}$ formula in the sense of a formula that is both $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ ; rather, there are both $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ formulas that define the set.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] For example, the set of odd natural numbers n is definable by either $\forall k(n\neq 2\times k)$ or $\exists k(n=2\times k+1)$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A parallel definition is used to define the arithmetical hierarchy on finite Cartesian powers of the set of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Instead of formulas with one free variable, formulas with *k* free first-order variables are used to define the arithmetical hierarchy on sets of *k*-tuples of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] These are in fact related by the use of a pairing function.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The following meanings can be attached to the notation for the arithmetical hierarchy on formulas.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The subscript n in the symbols $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ indicates the number of alternations of blocks of universal and existential first-order quantifiers that are used in a formula.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Moreover, the outermost block is existential in $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ formulas and universal in $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ formulas.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The superscript 0 in the symbols $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ , $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ , and $\Delta _{n}^{0}$ indicates the type of the objects being quantified over.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Type 0 objects are natural numbers, and objects of type $i+1$ are functions that map the set of objects of type i to the natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Quantification over higher type objects, such as functions from natural numbers to natural numbers, is described by a superscript greater than 0, as in the analytical hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The superscript 0 indicates quantifiers over numbers, the superscript 1 would indicate quantification over functions from numbers to numbers (type 1 objects), the superscript 2 would correspond to quantification over functions that take a type 1 object and return a number, and so on.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] To do so, fix a set of natural numbers *Y* and add a predicate for membership of *Y* to the language of Peano arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] We then say that *X* is in $\Sigma _{n}^{0,Y}$ if it is defined by a $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ formula in this expanded language.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] In other words, *X* is $\Sigma _{n}^{0,Y}$ if it is defined by a $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ formula allowed to ask questions about membership of *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Alternatively one can view the $\Sigma _{n}^{0,Y}$ sets as those sets that can be built starting with sets recursive in *Y* and alternately taking unions and intersections of these sets up to *n* times.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] For example, let *Y* be a set of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Let *X* be the set of numbers divisible by an element of *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Then *X* is defined by the formula $\phi (n)=\exists m\exists t(Y(m)\land m\times t=n)$ so *X* is in $\Sigma _{1}^{0,Y}$ (actually it is in $\Delta _{0}^{0,Y}$ as well, since we could bound both quantifiers by *n*).
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Arithmetical reducibility is an intermediate notion between Turing reducibility and hyperarithmetic reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A set is **arithmetical** (also **arithmetic** and **arithmetically definable**) if it is defined by some formula in the language of Peano arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Equivalently *X* is arithmetical if *X* is $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ or $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ for some natural number *n*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A set *X* **is arithmetical in** a set *Y*, denoted $X\leq _{A}Y$ , if *X* is definable as some formula in the language of Peano arithmetic extended by a predicate for membership of *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Equivalently, *X* is arithmetical in *Y* if *X* is in $\Sigma _{n}^{0,Y}$ or $\Pi _{n}^{0,Y}$ for some natural number *n*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A synonym for $X\leq _{A}Y$ is: *X* is **arithmetically reducible** to *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The equivalence classes of this relation are called the **arithmetic degrees**; they are partially ordered under $\leq _{A}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The Cantor space, denoted $2^{\omega }$ , is the set of all infinite sequences of 0s and 1s; the Baire space, denoted $\omega ^{\omega }$ or ${\mathcal {N}}$ , is the set of all infinite sequences of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Note that elements of the Cantor space can be identified with sets of natural numbers and elements of the Baire space with functions from natural numbers to natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The ordinary axiomatization of second-order arithmetic uses a set-based language in which the set quantifiers can naturally be viewed as quantifying over Cantor space.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A subset of Cantor space is assigned the classification $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ if it is definable by a $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ formula.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The set is assigned the classification $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ if it is definable by a $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ formula.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] If the set is both $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ then it is given the additional classification $\Delta _{n}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] For example, let $O\subseteq 2^{\omega }$ be the set of all infinite binary strings that aren't all 0 (or equivalently the set of all non-empty sets of natural numbers).
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Note that while both the elements of the Cantor space (regarded as sets of natural numbers) and subsets of the Cantor space are classified in arithmetic hierarchies, these are not the same hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] In fact the relationship between the two hierarchies is interesting and non-trivial.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] For instance the $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ elements of the Cantor space are not (in general) the same as the elements X of the Cantor space so that $\{X\}$ is a $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ subset of the Cantor space.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] However, many interesting results relate the two hierarchies.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] There are two ways that a subset of Baire space can be classified in the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A parallel definition is used to define the arithmetical hierarchy on finite Cartesian powers of Baire space or Cantor space, using formulas with several free variables.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The arithmetical hierarchy can be defined on any effective Polish space; the definition is particularly simple for Cantor space and Baire space because they fit with the language of ordinary second-order arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Note that we can also define the arithmetic hierarchy of subsets of the Cantor and Baire spaces relative to some set of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] In fact boldface $\mathbf {\Sigma } _{n}^{0}$ is just the union of $\Sigma _{n}^{0,Y}$ for all sets of natural numbers *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Note that the boldface hierarchy is just the standard hierarchy of Borel sets.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] It is possible to define the arithmetical hierarchy of formulas using a language extended with a function symbol for each primitive recursive function.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The class $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ and thus all higher classes in the hierarchy remain unaffected.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] A more semantic variation of the hierarchy can be defined on all finitary relations on the natural numbers; the following definition is used.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The classifications $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ and $\Pi _{n}^{0}$ are defined inductively with the following rules.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] This variation slightly changes the classification of some sets.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] In particular, $\Sigma _{0}^{0}=\Pi _{0}^{0}=\Delta _{0}^{0}$ , as a class of sets (definable by the relations in the class), is identical to $\Delta _{1}^{0}$ as the latter was formerly defined.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] It can be extended to cover finitary relations on the natural numbers, Baire space, and Cantor space.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The following properties hold for the arithmetical hierarchy of sets of natural numbers and the arithmetical hierarchy of subsets of Cantor or Baire space.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] If *S* is a Turing computable set, then both *S* and its complement are recursively enumerable (if *T* is a Turing machine giving 1 for inputs in *S* and 0 otherwise, we may build a Turing machine halting only on the former, and another halting only on the latter).
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] By Post's theorem, both *S* and its complement are in $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Similarly, for every set *S* in $\Delta _{1}^{0}$ , both *S* and its complement are in $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ and are therefore (by Post's theorem) recursively enumerable by some Turing machines *T*1 and *T*2, respectively.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] For every number *n*, exactly one of these halts.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] We may therefore construct a Turing machine *T* that alternates between *T*1 and *T*2, halting and returning 1 when the former halts or halting and returning 0 when the latter halts.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Thus *T* halts on every *n* and returns whether it is in *S*; so *S* is computable.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The Turing computable sets of natural numbers are exactly the sets at level $\Delta _{1}^{0}$ of the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The recursively enumerable sets are exactly the sets at level $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] No oracle machine is capable of solving its own halting problem (a variation of Turing's proof applies).
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The halting problem for a $\Delta _{n}^{0,Y}$ oracle in fact sits in $\Sigma _{n+1}^{0,Y}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] Post's theorem establishes a close connection between the arithmetical hierarchy of sets of natural numbers and the Turing degrees.
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] The polynomial hierarchy is a "feasible resource-bounded" version of the arithmetical hierarchy in which polynomial length bounds are placed on the numbers involved (or, equivalently, polynomial time bounds are placed on the Turing machines involved).
[src:recursion-theory/arithmetical-hierarchy] It gives a finer classification of some sets of natural numbers that are at level $\Delta _{1}^{0}$ of the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The study of which mathematical constructions can be effectively performed is sometimes called **recursive mathematics**.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory originated in the 1930s, with the work of Kurt Gödel, Alonzo Church, Rózsa Péter, Alan Turing, Stephen Kleene, and Emil Post.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The fundamental results the researchers obtained established Turing computability as the correct formalization of the informal idea of effective calculation.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1952, these results led Kleene to coin the two names "Church's thesis" and "Turing's thesis".
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Nowadays these are often considered as a single hypothesis, the Church–Turing thesis, which states that any function that is computable by an algorithm is a computable function.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] With a definition of effective calculation came the first proofs that there are problems in mathematics that cannot be effectively decided.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1936, Church and Turing (inspired by techniques used by Gödel to prove his incompleteness theorems) independently demonstrated that the *Entscheidungsproblem* is not effectively decidable.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This result showed that there is no algorithmic procedure that can correctly decide whether arbitrary mathematical propositions are true or false.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Many problems in mathematics have been shown to be undecidable after these initial examples were established.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1947, Markov and Post published independent papers showing that the word problem for semigroups cannot be effectively decided.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The main form of computability studied in the field was introduced by Turing in 1936.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A set of natural numbers is said to be a *computable set* (also called a *decidable*, *recursive*, or *Turing computable* set) if there is a Turing machine that, given a number *n*, halts with output 1 if *n* is in the set and halts with output 0 if *n* is not in the set.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A function *f* from natural numbers to natural numbers is a *(Turing) computable,* or *recursive function* if there is a Turing machine that, on input *n*, halts and returns output *f*(*n*).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The use of Turing machines here is not necessary; there are many other models of computation that have the same computing power as Turing machines; for example the μ-recursive functions obtained from primitive recursion and the μ operator.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The terminology for computable functions and sets is not completely standardized.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The definition in terms of μ-recursive functions as well as a different definition of *rekursiv* functions by Gödel led to the traditional name *recursive* for sets and functions computable by a Turing machine.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The word *decidable* stems from the German word *Entscheidungsproblem*, which was used in the original papers of Turing and others.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In contemporary use, the term "computable function" has various definitions: according to Nigel J.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Cutland, it is a partial recursive function (which can be undefined for some inputs), while according to Robert I.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This article follows the second of these conventions.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1996, Soare gave additional comments about the terminology.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Not every set of natural numbers is computable.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The halting problem, which is the set of (descriptions of) Turing machines that halt on input 0, is a well-known example of a noncomputable set.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The existence of many noncomputable sets follows from the facts that there are only countably many Turing machines, and thus only countably many computable sets, but according to the Cantor's theorem, there are uncountably many sets of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Although the halting problem is not computable, it is possible to simulate program execution and produce an infinite list of the programs that do halt.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Thus the halting problem is an example of a *computably enumerable (c.e.) set*, which is a set that can be enumerated by a Turing machine (other terms for computably enumerable include *recursively enumerable* and *semidecidable*).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Equivalently, a set is c.e. if and only if it is the range of some computable function.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The c.e. sets, although not decidable in general, have been studied in detail in computability theory.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Beginning with the theory of computable sets and functions described above, the field of computability theory has grown to include the study of many closely related topics.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These are not independent areas of research: each of these areas draws ideas and results from the others, and most computability theorists are familiar with the majority of them.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory in mathematical logic has traditionally focused on *relative computability*, a generalization of Turing computability defined using oracle Turing machines, introduced by Turing in 1939.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] An oracle Turing machine is a hypothetical device that, in addition to performing the actions of a regular Turing machine, is able to ask questions to an *oracle*, which is a particular set of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The oracle machine may only ask questions of the form "Is *n* in the oracle set?".
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Each question will be immediately answered correctly, even if the oracle set is not computable.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Thus an oracle machine with a noncomputable oracle will be able to compute sets that a Turing machine without an oracle cannot.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Informally, a set of natural numbers *A* is *Turing reducible* to a set *B* if there is an oracle machine that correctly tells whether numbers are in *A* when run with *B* as the oracle set (in this case, the set *A* is also said to be (*relatively*) *computable from* *B* and *recursive in* *B*).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] If a set *A* is Turing reducible to a set *B* and *B* is Turing reducible to *A* then the sets are said to have the same *Turing degree* (also called *degree of unsolvability*).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The Turing degree of a set gives a precise measure of how uncomputable the set is.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Each can be translated into any other via a many-one reduction.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] That is, given such sets *A* and *B*, there is a total computable function *f* such that *A* = {*x* : *f*(*x*) ∈ *B*}.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These sets are said to be *many-one equivalent* (or *m-equivalent*).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Many-one reducibility is "stronger" than Turing reducibility: if a set *A* is many-one reducible to a set *B*, then *A* is Turing reducible to *B*, but the converse does not always hold.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Although the natural examples of noncomputable sets are all many-one equivalent, it is possible to construct computably enumerable sets *A* and *B* such that *A* is Turing reducible to *B* but not many-one reducible to *B*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] It can be shown that every computably enumerable set is many-one reducible to the halting problem, and thus the halting problem is the most complicated computably enumerable set with respect to many-one reducibility and with respect to Turing reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1944, Post asked whether *every* computably enumerable set is either computable or Turing equivalent to the halting problem, that is, whether there is no computably enumerable set with a Turing degree intermediate between those two.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] As intermediate results, Post defined natural types of computably enumerable sets like the simple, hypersimple and hyperhypersimple sets.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post showed that these sets are strictly between the computable sets and the halting problem with respect to many-one reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post also showed that some of them are strictly intermediate under other reducibility notions stronger than Turing reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] But Post left open the main problem of the existence of computably enumerable sets of intermediate Turing degree; this problem became known as *Post's problem*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] After ten years, Kleene and Post showed in 1954 that there are intermediate Turing degrees between those of the computable sets and the halting problem, but they failed to show that any of these degrees contains a computably enumerable set.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Very soon after this, Friedberg and Muchnik independently solved Post's problem by establishing the existence of computably enumerable sets of intermediate degree.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This groundbreaking result opened a wide study of the Turing degrees of the computably enumerable sets, which turned out to possess a very complicated and non-trivial structure.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] There are uncountably many sets that are not computably enumerable, and the investigation of the Turing degrees of all sets is as central in computability theory as the investigation of the computably enumerable Turing degrees.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The study of arbitrary (not necessarily computably enumerable) Turing degrees involves the study of the Turing jump.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Given a set *A*, the *Turing jump* of *A* is a set of natural numbers encoding a solution to the halting problem for oracle Turing machines running with oracle *A*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The Turing jump of any set is always of higher Turing degree than the original set, and a theorem of Friedburg shows that any set that computes the halting problem can be obtained as the Turing jump of another set.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post's theorem establishes a close relationship between the Turing jump operation and the arithmetical hierarchy, which is a classification of certain subsets of the natural numbers based on their definability in arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Much recent research on Turing degrees has focused on the overall structure of the set of Turing degrees and the set of Turing degrees containing computably enumerable sets.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A deep theorem of Shore and Slaman states that the function mapping a degree *x* to the degree of its Turing jump is definable in the partial order of the Turing degrees.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A survey by Ambos-Spies and Fejer gives an overview of this research and its historical progression.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] An ongoing area of research in computability theory studies reducibility relations other than Turing reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post introduced several *strong reducibilities*, so named because they imply truth-table reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A Turing machine implementing a strong reducibility will compute a total function regardless of which oracle it is presented with.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] *Weak reducibilities* are those where a reduction process may not terminate for all oracles; Turing reducibility is one example.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] via an oracle Turing machine that computes a total function regardless of the oracle it is given.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Many variants of truth-table reducibility have also been studied.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Further reducibilities (positive, disjunctive, conjunctive, linear and their weak and bounded versions) are discussed in the article Reduction (computability theory).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The major research on strong reducibilities has been to compare their theories, both for the class of all computably enumerable sets as well as for the class of all subsets of the natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Furthermore, the relations between the reducibilities has been studied.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] For example, it is known that every Turing degree is either a truth-table degree or is the union of infinitely many truth-table degrees.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Reducibilities weaker than Turing reducibility (that is, reducibilities that are implied by Turing reducibility) have also been studied.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The most well known are arithmetical reducibility and hyperarithmetical reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These reducibilities are closely connected to definability over the standard model of arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] But, many of these index sets are even more complicated than the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These type of sets can be classified using the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] For example, the index set FIN of the class of all finite sets is on the level Σ2, the index set REC of the class of all recursive sets is on the level Σ3, the index set COFIN of all cofinite sets is also on the level Σ3 and the index set COMP of the class of all Turing-complete sets Σ4.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These hierarchy levels are defined inductively, Σ*n*+1 contains just all sets that are computably enumerable relative to Σ*n*; Σ1 contains the computably enumerable sets.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The index sets given here are even complete for their levels, that is, all the sets in these levels can be many-one reduced to the given index sets.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The program of *reverse mathematics* asks which set-existence axioms are necessary to prove particular theorems of mathematics in subsystems of second-order arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This study was initiated by Harvey Friedman and was studied in detail by Stephen Simpson and others; in 1999, Simpson gave a detailed discussion of the program.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The set-existence axioms in question correspond informally to axioms saying that the powerset of the natural numbers is closed under various reducibility notions.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The weakest such axiom studied in reverse mathematics is *recursive comprehension*, which states that the powerset of the naturals is closed under Turing reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A numbering is an enumeration of functions; it has two parameters, *e* and *x* and outputs the value of the *e*-th function in the numbering on the input *x*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Numberings can be partial-computable although some of its members are total computable functions.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Admissible numberings are those into which all others can be translated.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A Friedberg numbering (named after its discoverer) is a one-one numbering of all partial-computable functions; it is necessarily not an admissible numbering.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Later research dealt also with numberings of other classes like classes of computably enumerable sets.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Goncharov discovered for example a class of computably enumerable sets for which the numberings fall into exactly two classes with respect to computable isomorphisms.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post's problem was solved with a method called the *priority method*; a proof using this method is called a *priority argument*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This method is primarily used to construct computably enumerable sets with particular properties.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] To use this method, the desired properties of the set to be constructed are broken up into an infinite list of goals, known as *requirements*, so that satisfying all the requirements will cause the set constructed to have the desired properties.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Each requirement is assigned to a natural number representing the priority of the requirement; so 0 is assigned to the most important priority, 1 to the second most important, and so on.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The set is then constructed in stages, each stage attempting to satisfy one of more of the requirements by either adding numbers to the set or banning numbers from the set so that the final set will satisfy the requirement.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] It may happen that satisfying one requirement will cause another to become unsatisfied; the priority order is used to decide what to do in such an event.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Priority arguments have been employed to solve many problems in computability theory, and have been classified into a hierarchy based on their complexity.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Because complex priority arguments can be technical and difficult to follow, it has traditionally been considered desirable to prove results without priority arguments, or to see if results proved with priority arguments can also be proved without them.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] For example, Kummer published a paper on a proof for the existence of Friedberg numberings without using the priority method.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] When Post defined the notion of a simple set as a c.e. set with an infinite complement not containing any infinite c.e. set, he started to study the structure of the computably enumerable sets under inclusion.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This lattice became a well-studied structure.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Computable sets can be defined in this structure by the basic result that a set is computable if and only if the set and its complement are both computably enumerable.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Infinite c.e. sets have always infinite computable subsets; but on the other hand, simple sets exist but do not always have a coinfinite computable superset.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post introduced already hypersimple and hyperhypersimple sets; later maximal sets were constructed, which are c.e. sets such that every c.e. superset is either a finite variant of the given maximal set or is co-finite.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post's original motivation in the study of this lattice was to find a structural notion such that every set that satisfies this property is neither in the Turing degree of the computable sets nor in the Turing degree of the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Post did not find such a property and the solution to his problem applied priority methods instead; in 1991, Harrington and Soare eventually found such a property.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Another important question is the existence of automorphisms in computability-theoretic structures.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] One of these structures is that one of computably enumerable sets under inclusion modulo finite difference; in this structure, *A* is below *B* if and only if the set difference *B* − *A* is finite.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Maximal sets (as defined in the previous paragraph) have the property that they cannot be automorphic to non-maximal sets, that is, if there is an automorphism of the computably enumerable sets under the structure just mentioned, then every maximal set is mapped to another maximal set.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1974, Soare showed that also the converse holds, that is, every two maximal sets are automorphic.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] So the maximal sets form an orbit, that is, every automorphism preserves maximality and any two maximal sets are transformed into each other by some automorphism.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Harrington gave a further example of an automorphic property: that of the creative sets, the sets that are many-one equivalent to the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Besides the lattice of computably enumerable sets, automorphisms are also studied for the structure of the Turing degrees of all sets as well as for the structure of the Turing degrees of c.e. sets.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The main idea is to consider a universal Turing machine *U* and to measure the complexity of a number (or string) *x* as the length of the shortest input *p* such that *U*(*p*) outputs *x*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This approach revolutionized earlier ways to determine when an infinite sequence (equivalently, characteristic function of a subset of the natural numbers) is random or not by invoking a notion of randomness for finite objects.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Kolmogorov complexity became not only a subject of independent study but is also applied to other subjects as a tool for obtaining proofs.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] There are still many open problems in this area.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Such sets are known as (*m*, *n*)-recursive sets.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The first major result in this branch of computability theory is Trakhtenbrot's result that a set is computable if it is (*m*, *n*)-recursive for some *m*, *n* with 2*m* > *n*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] On the other hand, Jockusch's semirecursive sets (which were already known informally before Jockusch introduced them 1968) are examples of a sets that are (*m*, *n*)-recursive if and only if 2*m* < *n* + 1.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] There are uncountably many of these sets and also some computably enumerable but noncomputable sets of this type.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Later, Degtev established a hierarchy of computably enumerable sets that are (1, *n* + 1)-recursive but not (1, *n*)-recursive.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] After a long phase of research by Russian scientists, this subject became repopularized in the west by Beigel's thesis on bounded queries, which linked frequency computation to the above-mentioned bounded reducibilities and other related notions.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] This is the computability-theoretic branch of learning theory.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Mark Gold's model of learning in the limit from 1967 and has developed since then more and more models of learning.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The general scenario is the following: Given a class *S* of computable functions, is there a learner (that is, computable functional) that outputs for any input of the form (*f*(0), *f*(1), ..., *f*(*n*)) a hypothesis.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A learner *M* learns a function *f* if almost all hypotheses are the same index *e* of *f* with respect to a previously agreed on acceptable numbering of all computable functions; *M* learns *S* if *M* learns every *f* in *S*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Basic results are that all computably enumerable classes of functions are learnable while the class REC of all computable functions is not learnable.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Many related models have been considered and also the learning of classes of computably enumerable sets from positive data is a topic studied from Gold's pioneering paper in 1967 onwards.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory includes the study of generalized notions of this field such as arithmetic reducibility, hyperarithmetical reducibility and α-recursion theory, as described by Sacks in 1990.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These generalized notions include reducibilities that cannot be executed by Turing machines but are nevertheless natural generalizations of Turing reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These studies include approaches to investigate the analytical hierarchy, which differs from the arithmetical hierarchy by permitting quantification over sets of natural numbers in addition to quantification over individual numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These areas are linked to the theories of well-orderings and trees; for example the set of all indices of computable (nonbinary) trees without infinite branches is complete for level $\Pi _{1}^{1}$ of the analytical hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Both Turing reducibility and hyperarithmetical reducibility are important in the field of effective descriptive set theory.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The even more general notion of degrees of constructibility is studied in set theory.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory for digital computation is well developed.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory is less well developed for analog computation that occurs in analog computers, analog signal processing, analog electronics, artificial neural networks and continuous-time control theory, modelled by differential equations and continuous dynamical systems.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] For example, models of computation such as the Blum–Shub–Smale machine model have formalized computation on the reals.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] There are close relationships between the Turing degree of a set of natural numbers and the difficulty (in terms of the arithmetical hierarchy) of defining that set using a first-order formula.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] One such relationship is made precise by Post's theorem.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] A weaker relationship was demonstrated by Kurt Gödel in the proofs of his completeness theorem and incompleteness theorems.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Gödel's proofs show that the set of logical consequences of an effective first-order theory is a computably enumerable set, and that if the theory is strong enough this set will be uncomputable.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Similarly, Tarski's indefinability theorem can be interpreted both in terms of definability and in terms of computability.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory is also linked to second-order arithmetic, a formal theory of natural numbers and sets of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The fact that certain sets are computable or relatively computable often implies that these sets can be defined in weak subsystems of second-order arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The program of reverse mathematics uses these subsystems to measure the non-computability inherent in well known mathematical theorems.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1999, Simpson discussed many aspects of second-order arithmetic and reverse mathematics.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The field of proof theory includes the study of second-order arithmetic and Peano arithmetic, as well as formal theories of the natural numbers weaker than Peano arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] One method of classifying the strength of these weak systems is by characterizing which computable functions the system can prove to be total.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] For example, in primitive recursive arithmetic any computable function that is provably total is actually primitive recursive, while Peano arithmetic proves that functions like the Ackermann function, which are not primitive recursive, are total.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Not every total computable function is provably total in Peano arithmetic, however; an example of such a function is provided by Goodstein's theorem.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The field of mathematical logic dealing with computability and its generalizations has been called "recursion theory" since its early days.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Soare, a prominent researcher in the field, has proposed that the field should be called "computability theory" instead.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] He argues that Turing's terminology using the word "computable" is more natural and more widely understood than the terminology using the word "recursive" introduced by Kleene.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Many contemporary researchers have begun to use this alternate terminology.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] These researchers also use terminology such as *partial computable function* and *computably enumerable*(*c.e.*)*set* instead of *partial recursive function* and *recursively enumerable*(*r.e.*)*set*.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Not all researchers have been convinced, however, as explained by Fortnow and Simpson.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Some commentators argue that both the names *recursion theory* and *computability theory* fail to convey the fact that most of the objects studied in computability theory are not computable.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] In 1967, Rogers suggested that a key property of computability theory is that its results and structures should be invariant under computable bijections on the natural numbers (this suggestion draws on the ideas of the Erlangen program in geometry).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The idea is that a computable bijection merely renames numbers in a set, rather than indicating any structure in the set, much as a rotation of the Euclidean plane does not change any geometric aspect of lines drawn on it.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] Since any two infinite computable sets are linked by a computable bijection, this proposal identifies all the infinite computable sets (the finite computable sets are viewed as trivial).
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] According to Rogers, the sets of interest in computability theory are the noncomputable sets, partitioned into equivalence classes by computable bijections of the natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The main professional organization for computability theory is the *Association for Symbolic Logic*, which holds several research conferences each year.
[src:recursion-theory/computability-theory] The interdisciplinary research Association *Computability in Europe* (*CiE*) also organizes a series of annual conferences.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In computability theory, the **halting problem** is the decision problem of determining, from a description of an arbitrary computer program and an input, whether the program will eventually halt (finish running) or continue to run forever.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Alan Turing proved in 1937 that the halting problem is *undecidable*, meaning that no general algorithm exists that can correctly solve the problem for all possible program–input pairs.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The problem comes up often in discussions of computability since it demonstrates that some functions are mathematically definable but not computable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A key part of the formal statement of the problem is a mathematical definition of a computer and program, usually via a Turing machine.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The proof then shows, for any program *f* that might determine whether programs halt, that a "pathological" program *g* exists for which *f* makes an incorrect determination.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Specifically, *g* is the program that, when called with some input, passes its own source and its input to *f* and does the opposite of what *f* predicts *g* will do.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The behavior of *f* on *g* shows undecidability as it means no program *f* will solve the halting problem in every possible case.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is a decision problem about properties of computer programs on a fixed Turing-complete model of computation.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This model of computation includes all programs in Turing-equivalent programming languages.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Given a program and an input, the question is whether the program will eventually halt when run with that particular input.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In this abstract framework, there are no limitations on the memory or time required for the program's execution; the program may run arbitrarily long and consume arbitrarily large amounts of storage before halting.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] never halts; rather, it goes on forever in an infinite loop.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Simple cases like these are easy to decide, but more complex programs are not.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Turing proved no algorithm exists that always correctly decides whether, for a given arbitrary program and input, the program halts when run with that input.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The essence of Turing's proof is that any such algorithm can be made to produce contradictory output and therefore cannot be correct.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Some infinite loops can be quite useful.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] For instance, event loops are typically coded as infinite loops.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Most subroutines, however, are intended to finish.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In hard real-time computing, subroutines must not only finish, but finish before a given deadline.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In order to meet these requirements, programmers apply the rule of least power and use restricted styles, not quite fully Turing-complete, that make it easy to prove that the resulting subroutines finish before the given deadline.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] These include languages such as MISRA C, SPARK, and Rocq.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem requires a decision procedure that works for all programs and inputs.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] But for any specific program and input, the answer is simply "halts" or "does not halt".
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Consider two simple decision procedures, one that always answers "halts" and another that always answers "does not halt".
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] For any given case, one of these two algorithms answers correctly, yet neither algorithm solves the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Interpreters are programs that simulate the execution of programs whatever source code they are given.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Such programs can demonstrate that a program does halt, by running the program for some number of steps.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, an interpreter will not halt if its input program does not halt, so this approach cannot solve the halting problem as stated; it does not successfully answer "does not halt" for programs that do not halt, or determine whether a program will eventually halt or run forever.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is decidable for linear bounded automata (LBAs) or deterministic machines with finite memory.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] For nondeterministic finite memory machines, it is also decidable whether the machine halts on none, some, or all of the possible sequences of nondeterministic decisions, by enumerating states after each possible decision.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In April 1936, Alonzo Church published his proof of the undecidability of a problem in the lambda calculus.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Turing's proof was published later, in January 1937.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Since then, many other undecidable problems have been described, including the halting problem which emerged in the 1950s.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Many papers and textbooks refer the definition and proof of undecidability of the halting problem to Turing's 1936 paper.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Turing did not use the terms "halt" or "halting" in any of his published works, including his 1936 paper.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A search of the academic literature from 1936 to 1958 showed that the first published material using the term "halting problem" was Rogers (1957).
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, Rogers says he had a draft of Davis (1958) available to him, and Martin Davis states in the introduction that "the expert will perhaps find some novelty in the arrangement and treatment of topics", so the terminology must be attributed to Davis.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Davis stated in a letter that he had been referring to the halting problem since 1952.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is Turing equivalent to both Davis's printing problem ("does a Turing machine starting from a given state ever print a given symbol?") and to the printing problem considered in Turing's 1936 paper ("does a Turing machine starting from a blank tape ever print a given symbol?").
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, Turing equivalence is rather loose and does not mean that the two problems are the same.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] There are machines which print but do not halt, and halt but not print.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The printing and halting problems address different issues and exhibit important conceptual and technical differences.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In theoretical computer science, a decision problem is any problem that can be phrased as a yes–no question about a mathematical object.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Given the description of a program (P) and an input (x), does (P(x)) eventually halt?
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The conventional representation of decision problems is the set of objects possessing the property in question.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This set is recursively enumerable, which means there is a computable function that lists all of the pairs (*i*, *x*) it contains.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, the complement of this set is not recursively enumerable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A decision problem is said to be *decidable* if there exists an algorithm that always halts with the correct answer, and an undecidable problem if no such algorithm exists.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In his original proof Turing formalized the concept of *algorithm* by introducing Turing machines.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, the result is in no way specific to them; it applies equally to any other model of computation that is equivalent in its computational power to Turing machines, such as Markov algorithms, Lambda calculus, Post systems, register machines, or tag systems.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] What is important is that the formalization allows a straightforward mapping of algorithms to some data type that the algorithm can operate upon.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The mapping to strings is usually the most straightforward, but strings over an alphabet with *n* characters can also be mapped to numbers by interpreting them as numbers in an *n*-ary numeral system.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] There are many undecidable problems; any set whose Turing degree equals that of the halting problem is such a formulation.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Christopher Strachey outlined a proof by contradiction that the halting problem is not solvable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The proof proceeds as follows: Suppose that there exists a total computable function *halts(f)* that returns true if the subroutine *f* halts (when run with no inputs) and returns false otherwise.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The concept above shows the general method of the proof, but the computable function *halts* does not directly take a subroutine as an argument; instead it takes the source code of a program.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Moreover, the definition of *g* is self-referential.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A rigorous proof addresses these issues.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Here *program i* refers to the *i* th program in an enumeration of all the programs of a fixed Turing-complete model of computation.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Possible values for a total computable function *f* arranged in a 2D array.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The values of *f*(*i*,*i*) and *g*(*i*) are shown at the bottom; *U* indicates that the function *g* is undefined for a particular input value.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The proof proceeds by directly establishing that no total computable function with two arguments can be the required function *h*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Because *g* is partial computable, there must be a program *e* that computes *g*, by the assumption that the model of computation is Turing-complete.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This program is one of all the programs on which the halting function *h* is defined.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The next step of the proof shows that *h*(*e*,*e*) will not have the same value as *f*(*e*,*e*).
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In either case, *f* cannot be the same function as *h*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Because *f* was an *arbitrary* total computable function with two arguments, all such functions must differ from *h*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This proof is analogous to Cantor's diagonal argument.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] One may visualize a two-dimensional array with one column and one row for each natural number, as indicated in the table above.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The value of *f*(*i*,*j*) is placed at column *i*, row *j*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Because *f* is assumed to be a total computable function, any element of the array can be calculated using *f*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The construction of the function *g* can be visualized using the main diagonal of this array.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] If the array has a 0 at position (*i*,*i*), then *g*(*i*) is 0.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The contradiction comes from the fact that there is some column *e* of the array corresponding to *g* itself.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Now assume *f* was the halting function *h*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Similarly, if *g*(*e*) is not defined, then program *e* does not halt on input *e*, thus *f*(*e,e*) = 0, which leads to *g*(*e*) = 0 under *g'*s construction.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This contradicts the assumption of *g*(*e*) not being defined.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Therefore any arbitrary computable function *f* cannot be the halting function *h*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A typical method of proving a problem P to be undecidable is to *reduce* the halting problem to P .
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] For example, there cannot be a general algorithm that decides whether a given statement about natural numbers is true or false.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The reason for this is that the proposition stating that a certain program will halt given a certain input can be converted into an equivalent statement about natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] If an algorithm could find the truth value of every statement about natural numbers, it could certainly find the truth value of this one; but that would determine whether the original program halts.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Rice's theorem generalizes the theorem that the halting problem is unsolvable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] It states that for *any* non-trivial property, there is no general decision procedure that, for all programs, decides whether the partial function implemented by the input program has that property.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] (A partial function is a function which may not always produce a result, and so is used to model programs, which can either produce results or fail to halt.) For example, the property "halt for the input 0" is undecidable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Here, "non-trivial" means that the set of partial functions that satisfy the property is neither the empty set nor the set of all partial functions.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] For example, "halt on input 0 within 100 steps" is *not* a property of the partial function that is implemented by the program—it is a property of the program implementing the partial function and is very much decidable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Gregory Chaitin has defined a halting probability, represented by the symbol Ω, a type of real number that informally is said to represent the probability that a randomly produced program halts.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] These numbers have the same Turing degree as the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] It is a normal and transcendental number which can be defined but cannot be completely computed.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This means one can prove that there is no algorithm which produces the digits of Ω, although its first few digits can be calculated in simple cases.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Since the negative answer to the halting problem shows that there are problems that cannot be solved by a Turing machine, the Church–Turing thesis limits what can be accomplished by any machine that implements effective methods.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, not all machines conceivable to human imagination are subject to the Church–Turing thesis (e.g. oracle machines).
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] It is also an open question whether any such unknown physical processes are involved in the working of the human brain, and whether humans can solve the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Turing's proof shows that there can be no mechanical, general method (i.e., a Turing machine or a program in some equivalent model of computation) to determine whether algorithms halt.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, each individual instance of the halting problem has a definitive answer, which may or may not be practically computable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Given a specific algorithm and input, one can often show that it halts or does not halt, and in fact computer scientists often do just that as part of a correctness proof.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] There are some heuristics that can be used in an automated fashion to attempt to construct a proof, which frequently succeed on typical programs.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This field of research is known as automated termination analysis.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Some results have been established on the theoretical performance of halting problem heuristics, in particular the fraction of programs of a given size that may be correctly classified by a recursive algorithm.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] These results do not give precise numbers because the fractions are uncomputable and also highly dependent on the choice of program encoding used to determine "size".
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] For example, consider classifying programs by their number of states and using a specific "Turing semi-infinite tape" model of computation that errors (without halting) if the program runs off the left side of the tape.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Then $\lim _{n\to \infty }P(x\,{\text{halts is decidable}}\mid x\,{\text{has}}\,n\,{\text{states}})=1$ , over programs x chosen uniformly by number of states.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] But this result is in some sense "trivial" because these decidable programs are simply the ones that fall off the tape, and the heuristic is simply to predict not halting due to error.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Thus a seemingly irrelevant detail, namely the treatment of programs with errors, can turn out to be the deciding factor in determining the fraction of programs.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] To avoid these issues, several restricted notions of the "size" of a program have been developed.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] For example, a numbering that assigns indices $2^{n}$ to nontrivial programs and all other indices the error state is not dense, but there exists a dense Gödel numbering of syntactically correct Brainfuck programs.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A dense Gödel numbering is called optimal if, for any other Gödel numbering $\alpha$ , there is a 1-1 total recursive function f and a constant c such that for all i , $\alpha _{i}=\phi _{f(i)}$ and $f(i)\leq ci$ .
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This condition ensures that all programs have indices not much larger than their indices in any other Gödel numbering.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Optimal Gödel numberings are constructed by numbering the inputs of a universal Turing machine.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A third notion of size uses universal machines operating on binary strings and measures the length of the string needed to describe the input program.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A universal machine *U* is a machine for which every other machine *V* there exists a total computable function h such that $V(x)=U(h(x))$ .
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] An optimal machine is a universal machine that achieves the Kolmogorov complexity invariance bound, i.e. for every machine *V*, there exists *c* such that for all outputs *x*, if a *V*-program of length *n* outputs *x*, then there exists a *U*-program of at most length $n+c$ outputting *x*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] We consider partial computable functions (algorithms) A .
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The complex nature of these bounds is due to the oscillatory behavior of $\epsilon _{n}(A)$ .
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] There are infrequently occurring new varieties of programs that come in arbitrarily large "blocks", and a constantly growing fraction of repeats.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] If the blocks of new varieties are fully included, the error rate is at least $\epsilon$ , but between blocks the fraction of correctly categorized repeats can be arbitrarily high.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In particular a "tally" heuristic that simply remembers the first N inputs and recognizes their equivalents allows reaching an arbitrarily low error rate infinitely often.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The concepts raised by Gödel's incompleteness theorems are very similar to those raised by the halting problem, and the proofs are quite similar.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In fact, a weaker form of the First Incompleteness Theorem is an easy consequence of the undecidability of the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This weaker form differs from the standard statement of the incompleteness theorem by asserting that an effective axiomatization of the natural numbers that is both complete and sound is impossible.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The "sound" part is the weakening: it means that we require the axiomatic system in question to prove only *true* statements about natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Since soundness implies consistency, this weaker form can be seen as a corollary of the strong form.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] It is important to observe that the statement of the standard form of Gödel's First Incompleteness Theorem is completely unconcerned with the truth value of a statement, but only concerns the issue of whether it is possible to find it through a mathematical proof.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The weaker form of the theorem can be proved from the undecidability of the halting problem as follows.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Assume that we have a sound (and hence consistent) and complete effective axiomatization of all true first-order logic statements about natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Then we can build an algorithm that enumerates all these statements.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This means that there is an algorithm *N*(*n*) that, given a natural number *n*, computes a true first-order logic statement about natural numbers, and that for all true statements, there is at least one *n* such that *N*(*n*) yields that statement.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Now suppose we want to decide if the algorithm with representation *a* halts on input *i*.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] We know that this statement can be expressed with a first-order logic statement, say *H*(*a*, *i*).
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Since the axiomatization is complete it follows that either there is an *n* such that *N*(*n*) = *H*(*a*, *i*) or there is an *n′* such that *N*(*n′*) = ¬ *H*(*a*, *i*).
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] So if we iterate over all *n* until we either find *H*(*a*, *i*) or its negation, we will always halt, and furthermore, the answer it gives us will be true (by soundness).
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This means that this gives us an algorithm to decide the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Since we know that there cannot be such an algorithm, it follows that the assumption that there is a sound and complete effective axiomatization of all true first-order logic statements about natural numbers must be false.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Many variants of the halting problem can be found in computability textbooks.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Typically, these problems are RE-complete and describe sets of complexity $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ in the arithmetical hierarchy, the same as the standard halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The variants are thus undecidable, and the standard halting problem reduces to each variant and vice-versa.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However, some variants have a higher degree of unsolvability and cannot be reduced to the standard halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The *universal halting problem*, also known (in recursion theory) as *totality*, is the problem of determining whether a given computer program will halt *for every input* (the name *totality* comes from the equivalent question of whether the computed function is total).
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This problem is not only undecidable, as the halting problem is, but highly undecidable.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] In terms of the arithmetical hierarchy, it is $\Pi _{2}^{0}$ -complete.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] This means, in particular, that it cannot be decided even with an oracle for the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] There are many programs that, for some inputs, return a correct answer to the halting problem, while for other inputs they do not return an answer at all.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] However the problem "given program *p*, is it a partial halting solver" (in the sense described) is at least as hard as the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] To see this, assume that there is an algorithm PHSR ("partial halting solver recognizer") to do that.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] Then it can be used to solve the halting problem, as follows: To test whether input program *x* halts on *y*, construct a program *p* that on input (*x*,*y*) reports *true* and diverges on all other inputs.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A *lossy Turing machine* is a Turing machine in which part of the tape may non-deterministically disappear.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is decidable for a lossy Turing machine but non-primitive recursive.
[src:recursion-theory/halting-problem] A machine with an oracle for the halting problem can determine whether particular Turing machines will halt on particular inputs, but they cannot determine, in general, whether machines equivalent to themselves will halt.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] In computability theory, **Kleene's recursion theorems** are a pair of fundamental results about the application of computable functions to their own descriptions.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The theorems were first proved by Stephen Kleene in 1938 and appear in his 1952 book *Introduction to Metamathematics*.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] A related theorem, which constructs fixed points of a computable function, is known as **Rogers's theorem** and is due to Hartley Rogers, Jr.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The recursion theorems can be applied to construct fixed points of certain operations on computable functions, to generate quines, and to construct functions defined via recursive definitions.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The statement of the theorems refers to an admissible numbering $\varphi$ of the partial recursive functions, such that the function corresponding to index e is $\varphi _{e}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] If F and G are partial functions on the natural numbers, the notation $F\simeq G$ indicates that, for each *n*, either $F(n)$ and $G(n)$ are both defined and are equal, or else $F(n)$ and $G(n)$ are both undefined.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Given a function F on the natural numbers, a **fixed point** of F is an index e in the domain of F such that $\varphi _{e}\simeq \varphi _{F(e)}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Note that the comparison of in- and outputs here is not in terms of numerical values, but in terms of their associated partial recursive functions.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Rogers describes the following result as "a simpler version" of Kleene's (second) recursion theorem.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] This essentially means that if we apply an effective transformation to programs (say, replace instructions such as successor, jump, remove lines), there will always be a program whose behaviour is not altered by the transformation.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The proof uses a particular total computable function h , defined as follows.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] To complete the proof, let F be any total computable function, and construct h as above.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Let e be an index of the composition $F\circ h$ , which is a total computable function, so $\varphi _{e}(e)$ is defined.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Then $\varphi _{h(e)}\simeq \varphi _{\varphi _{e}(e)}$ by the definition of h .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] This proof is a construction of a partial recursive function that implements the Y combinator.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] A function F such that $\varphi _{e}\not \simeq \varphi _{F(e)}$ for all e is called **fixed-point free**.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The fixed-point theorem shows that no total computable function is fixed-point free, but there are many non-computable fixed-point-free functions.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] **Arslanov's completeness criterion** states that the only recursively enumerable Turing degree that computes a fixed-point-free function is **0′**, the degree of the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The second recursion theorem is a generalization of Rogers's theorem with a second input in the function.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] One informal interpretation of the second recursion theorem is that it is possible to construct self-referential programs; see "Application to quines" below.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The theorem can be proved from Rogers's theorem by letting F be a function such that $\varphi _{F(p)}(y)=Q(p,y)$ (a construction described by the S m n theorem).
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] One can then verify that a fixed-point of this F is an index p as required.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The theorem is constructive in the sense that a fixed computable function maps an index for Q into the index p .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Kleene's second recursion theorem and Rogers's theorem can both be proved, rather simply, from each other.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] However, a direct proof of Kleene's theorem does not make use of a universal program, which means that the theorem holds for certain subrecursive programming systems that do not have a universal program.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] A classic example using the second recursion theorem is the function $Q(x,y)=x$ .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The corresponding index p in this case yields a computable function that outputs its own index when applied to any value.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] When expressed as computer programs, such indices are known as **quines**.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The following example in Lisp illustrates how the p in the corollary can be effectively produced from the function Q .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The function `s11` in the code is the function of that name produced by the S m n theorem.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] `Q` can be changed to any two-argument function.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The second recursion theorem can be used to show that such equations define a computable function, where the notion of computability does not have to allow, prima facie, for recursive definitions (for example, it may be defined by μ-recursion, or by Turing machines).
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The recursion theorem establishes the existence of a computable function $\varphi _{f}$ such that $\varphi _{f}(x,y)\simeq \varphi _{F}(f,x,y)$ .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Thus f satisfies the given recursive definition.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Reflexive, or reflective, programming refers to the usage of self-reference in programs.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Jones presents a view of the second recursion theorem based on a reflexive language.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] It is shown that the reflexive language defined is not stronger than a language without reflection (because an interpreter for the reflexive language can be implemented without using reflection); then, it is shown that the recursion theorem is almost trivial in the reflexive language.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] While the second recursion theorem is about fixed points of computable functions, the first recursion theorem is related to fixed points determined by enumeration operators, which are a computable analogue of inductive definitions.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] An **enumeration operator** is a set of pairs (*A*,*n*) where *A* is a (code for a) finite set of numbers and *n* is a single natural number.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Often, *n* will be viewed as a code for an ordered pair of natural numbers, particularly when functions are defined via enumeration operators.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Enumeration operators are of central importance in the study of enumeration reducibility.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] A **recursive operator** is an enumeration operator that, when given the graph of a partial recursive function, always returns the graph of a partial recursive function.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] A fixed point of an enumeration operator Φ is a set *F* such that Φ(*F*) = *F*.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The first enumeration theorem shows that fixed points can be effectively obtained if the enumeration operator itself is computable.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] For any recursive operator Ψ there is a partial computable function φ such that Ψ(φ) = φ and φ is the smallest partial computable function with this property.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The first recursion theorem is also called Fixed point theorem (of recursion theory).
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Let $\Phi :\mathbb {F} (\mathbb {N} ^{k})\rightarrow (\mathbb {N} ^{k})$ be a recursive functional.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Then $\Phi$ has a least fixed point $f_{\Phi }:\mathbb {N} ^{k}\rightarrow \mathbb {N}$ which is computable i.e.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Like the second recursion theorem, the first recursion theorem can be used to obtain functions satisfying systems of recursion equations.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] To apply the first recursion theorem, the recursion equations must first be recast as a recursive operator.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Consider the recursion equations for the factorial function *f*: ${\begin{aligned}&f(0)=1\\&f(n+1)=(n+1)\cdot f(n)\end{aligned}}$ The corresponding recursive operator Φ will have information that tells how to get to the next value of *f* from the previous value.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] However, the recursive operator will actually define the graph of *f*.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] First, Φ will contain the pair $(\varnothing ,(0,1))$ .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] This indicates that *f*(0) is unequivocally 1, and thus the pair (0,1) is in the graph of *f*.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Unlike the base case *f*(0) = 1, the recursive operator requires some information about *f*(*n*) before it defines a value of *f*(*n* + 1).
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The first recursion theorem (in particular, part 1) states that there is a set *F* such that Φ(*F*) = F.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The set *F* will consist entirely of ordered pairs of natural numbers, and will be the graph of the factorial function *f*, as desired.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The restriction to recursion equations that can be recast as recursive operators ensures that the recursion equations actually define a least fixed point.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] For example, consider the set of recursion equations: ${\begin{aligned}&g(0)=1\\&g(n+1)=1\\&g(2n)=0\end{aligned}}$ There is no function *g* satisfying these equations, because they imply *g*(2) = 1 and also imply *g*(2) = 0.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Thus there is no fixed point *g* satisfying these recursion equations.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] It is possible to make an enumeration operator corresponding to these equations, but it will not be a recursive operator.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The proof of part 1 of the first recursion theorem is obtained by iterating the enumeration operator Φ beginning with the empty set.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] First, a sequence *F**k* is constructed, for $k=0,1,\ldots$ .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Finally, *F* is taken to be ${\textstyle \bigcup F_{k}}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The remainder of the proof consists of a verification that *F* is recursively enumerable and is the least fixed point of Φ.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The sequence *F**k* used in this proof corresponds to the Kleene chain in the proof of the Kleene fixed-point theorem.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The second part of the first recursion theorem follows from the first part.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The assumption that Φ is a recursive operator is used to show that the fixed point of Φ is the graph of a partial function.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The key point is that if the fixed point *F* is not the graph of a function, then there is some *k* such that *F**k* is not the graph of a function.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Compared to the second recursion theorem, the first recursion theorem produces a stronger conclusion but only when narrower hypotheses are satisfied.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] Rogers uses the term **weak recursion theorem** for the first recursion theorem and **strong recursion theorem** for the second recursion theorem.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] One difference between the first and second recursion theorems is that the fixed points obtained by the first recursion theorem are guaranteed to be least fixed points, while those obtained from the second recursion theorem may not be least fixed points.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] A second difference is that the first recursion theorem only applies to systems of equations that can be recast as recursive operators.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] This restriction is similar to the restriction to continuous operators in the Kleene fixed-point theorem of order theory.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] The second recursion theorem can be applied to any total recursive function.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] In the context of his theory of numberings, Ershov showed that Kleene's recursion theorem holds for any precomplete numbering.
[src:recursion-theory/kleene-s-recursion-theorem] A Gödel numbering is a precomplete numbering on the set of computable functions so the generalized theorem yields the Kleene recursion theorem as a special case.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] In computability theory, **Post's theorem**, named after Emil Post, describes the connection between the arithmetical hierarchy and the Turing degrees.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] The statement of Post's theorem uses several concepts relating to definability and computability theory.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] This section gives a brief overview of these concepts, which are covered in depth in their respective articles.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] The arithmetical hierarchy classifies certain sets of natural numbers that are definable in the language of first-order Peano arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] A formula is said to be $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ if it is an existential statement in prenex normal form (all quantifiers at the front) with m alternations between existential and universal quantifiers applied to a formula with bounded quantifiers only.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] where $\rho$ contains only bounded quantifiers and *Q* is $\forall$ if *m* is even and $\exists$ if *m* is odd.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] A set of natural numbers A is said to be $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ if it is definable by a $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ formula, that is, if there is a $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ formula $\phi (s)$ such that each number n is in A if and only if $\phi (n)$ holds.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] It is known that if a set is $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ then it is $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ for any $n>m$ , but for each *m* there is a $\Sigma _{m+1}^{0}$ set that is not $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Thus the number of quantifier alternations required to define a set gives a measure of the complexity of the set.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Post's theorem uses the relativized arithmetical hierarchy as well as the unrelativized hierarchy just defined.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] A set A of natural numbers is said to be $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ relative to a set B , written $\Sigma _{m}^{0,B}$ , if A is definable by a $\Sigma _{m}^{0}$ formula in an extended language that includes a predicate for membership in B .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] While the arithmetical hierarchy measures definability of sets of natural numbers, Turing degrees measure the level of uncomputability of sets of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] A set A is said to be Turing reducible to a set B , written $A\leq _{T}B$ , if there is an oracle Turing machine that, given an oracle for B , computes the characteristic function of A .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] The Turing jump of a set A is a form of the halting problem relative to A .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Given a set A , the Turing jump $A'$ is the set of indices of oracle Turing machines that halt on input 0 when run with oracle A .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] It is known that every set A is Turing reducible to its Turing jump, but the Turing jump of a set is never Turing reducible to the original set.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Post's theorem uses finitely iterated Turing jumps.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] For any set A of natural numbers, the notation $A^{(n)}$ indicates the n -fold iterated Turing jump of A .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Post's theorem establishes a close connection between the arithmetical hierarchy and the Turing degrees of the form $\emptyset ^{(n)}$ , that is, finitely iterated Turing jumps of the empty set.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] This means that every $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ set is many-one reducible to $\emptyset ^{(n)}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Post's theorem has many corollaries that expose additional relationships between the arithmetical hierarchy and the Turing degrees.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] A set is defined to be arithmetical if it is $\Sigma _{n}^{0}$ for some n .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Post's theorem shows that, equivalently, a set is arithmetical if and only if it is Turing reducible to $\emptyset ^{(m)}$ for some *m*.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] The operation of a Turing machine T on input n can be formalized logically in first-order arithmetic.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] For example, we may use symbols $A_{k}$ , $B_{k}$ , and $C_{k}$ for the tape configuration, machine state and location along the tape after k steps, respectively.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] T 's transition system determines the relation between $(A_{k},B_{k},C_{k})$ and $(A_{k+1},B_{k+1},C_{k+1})$ ; their initial values (for $k=0$ ) are the input, the initial state and zero, respectively.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] The machine halts if and only if there is a number k such that $B_{k}$ is the halting state.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Thus there is a formula $\varphi (n,n_{1})$ in first-order arithmetic with no unbounded quantifiers, such that T halts on input n at time at most $n_{1}$ if and only if $\varphi (n,n_{1})$ is satisfied.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] For a prefix-free Turing machine we may use, for input *n*, the initial tape configuration $t(n)=cat(2^{ceil(log_{2}n)}-1,0,n)$ where cat stands for concatenation; thus $t(n)$ is a $\log(n)$ -length string of $1-s$ followed by 0 and then by n .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] This is a first-order arithmetic formula with no unbounded quantifiers, i.e. it is in $\Sigma _{0}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Let S be a set that can be computably enumerated by a Turing machine.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Then there is a Turing machine T such that for every n , T halts when given n as an input if and only if n is in S .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] This can be formalized by the first-order arithmetical formula presented above.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Thus every computably enumerable set is in $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] The converse is true as well: for every formula $\varphi (n)$ in $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ with *k* existential quantifiers, we may enumerate the k -tuples of natural numbers and run a Turing machine that goes through all of them until it finds the formula is satisfied.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] This Turing machine halts on precisely the set of natural numbers satisfying $\varphi (n)$ , and thus enumerates its corresponding set.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] If the oracle is for a decision problem, $O_{m}$ is always "Yes" or "No", which we may formalize as 0 or 1.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Suppose the decision problem itself can be formalized by a first-order arithmetic formula $\psi ^{O}(m)$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] where ${\varphi _{O}}_{1}(n,n_{1})$ is a first-order formula with no unbounded quantifiers.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] If *O* is an oracle to the halting problem of a machine $T'$ , then $\psi ^{O}(m)$ is the same as "there exists $m_{1}$ such that $T'$ starting with input *m* is at the halting state after $m_{1}$ steps".
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Since there is a finite number of numbers *m* satisfying $m<2^{n_{1}}$ , we may choose the same number of steps for all of them: there is a number $m_{1}$ , such that $T'$ halts after $m_{1}$ steps precisely on those inputs $m<2^{n_{1}}$ for which it halts at all.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] (informally, there is a "maximal number of steps" $m_{1}$ such every oracle that does not halt within the first $m_{1}$ steps does not stop at all; however, for every $m_{2}$ , each oracle that halts after $m_{2}$ steps does halt).
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Note that we may replace both $n_{1}$ and $m_{1}$ by a single number - their maximum - without changing the truth value of $\varphi (n)$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Thus every set that is computably enumerable by an oracle machine with an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(1)}$ , is in $\Sigma _{2}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] The converse is true as well: Suppose $\varphi (n)$ is a formula in $\Sigma _{2}^{0}$ with $k_{1}$ existential quantifiers followed by $k_{2}$ universal quantifiers.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Equivalently, $\varphi (n)$ has $k_{1}$ > existential quantifiers followed by a negation of a formula in $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ ; the latter formula can be enumerated by a Turing machine and can thus be checked immediately by an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(1)}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] We may thus enumerate the $k_{1}$ -tuples of natural numbers and run an oracle machine with an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(1)}$ that goes through all of them until it finds a satisfaction for the formula.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] This oracle machine halts on precisely the set of natural numbers satisfying $\varphi (n)$ , and thus enumerates its corresponding set.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] More generally, suppose every set that is computably enumerable by an oracle machine with an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(p)}$ is in $\Sigma _{p+1}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Since $\psi ^{O}(m)$ is the same as $\varphi (n)$ for the previous Turing jump, it can be constructed (as we have just done with $\varphi (n)$ above) so that $\psi _{H}(m,m_{1})$ in $\Pi _{p}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] After moving to prenex formal form the new $\varphi (n)$ is in $\Sigma _{p+2}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] By induction, every set that is computably enumerable by an oracle machine with an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(p)}$ , is in $\Sigma _{p+1}^{0}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Now Suppose $\varphi (n)$ is a formula in $\Sigma _{p+2}^{0}$ with $k_{1}$ existential quantifiers followed by $k_{2}$ universal quantifiers etc.
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] Equivalently, $\varphi (n)$ has $k_{1}$ > existential quantifiers followed by a negation of a formula in $\Sigma _{p+1}^{0}$ ; the latter formula can be enumerated by an oracle machine with an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(p)}$ and can thus be checked immediately by an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(p+1)}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/post-s-theorem] We may thus enumerate the $k_{1}$ -tuples of natural numbers and run an oracle machine with an oracle for $\emptyset ^{(p+1)}$ that goes through all of them until it finds a satisfaction for the formula.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The first condition suggests why the term *semidecidable* is sometimes used.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] More precisely, if a number is in the set, one can *decide* this by running the algorithm, but if the number is not in the set, the algorithm can run forever, and no information is returned.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set that is "completely decidable" is a computable set.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The second condition suggests why *computably enumerable* is used.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The abbreviations **c.e.** and **r.e.** are often used, even in print, instead of the full phrase.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] In computational complexity theory, the complexity class containing all computably enumerable sets is RE.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] In recursion theory, the lattice of c.e. sets under inclusion is denoted ${\mathcal {E}}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set *S* of natural numbers is called **computably enumerable** if there is a partial computable function whose domain is exactly *S*, meaning that the function is defined if and only if its input is a member of *S*.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The equivalence of semidecidability and enumerability can be obtained by the technique of dovetailing.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The Diophantine characterizations of a computably enumerable set, while not as straightforward or intuitive as the first definitions, were found by Yuri Matiyasevich as part of the negative solution to Hilbert's Tenth Problem.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Diophantine sets predate recursion theory and are therefore historically the first way to describe these sets (although this equivalence was only remarked more than three decades after the introduction of computably enumerable sets).
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] If *A* and *B* are computably enumerable sets then *A* ∩ *B*, *A* ∪ *B* and *A* × *B* (with the ordered pair of natural numbers mapped to a single natural number with the Cantor pairing function) are computably enumerable sets.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The preimage of a computably enumerable set under a partial computable function is a computably enumerable set.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set T is called **co-computably-enumerable** or **co-c.e.** if its complement $\mathbb {N} \setminus T$ is computably enumerable.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Equivalently, a set is co-r.e. if and only if it is at level $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ of the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The complexity class of co-computably-enumerable sets is denoted co-RE.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set *A* is computable if and only if both *A* and the complement of *A* are computably enumerable.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Some pairs of computably enumerable sets are effectively separable and some are not.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The set of all recursively enumerable subsets of the natural numbers can be made into a poset under set inclusion; this poset is a lattice.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The theory of this lattice is known to be an undecidable problem.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Similarly, the set of all computably enumerable vector spaces also forms a lattice.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] In fact, one can generalize this even further to the lattice *L(Q)*, which is defined to consist of all recursively enumerable filters, where *Q* is some free Boolean algebra without any atoms.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] These lattices are closely tied to the study of recursively enumerable Pi-0-1 classes.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The intervals of this lattice are either boolean algebras, or their first-order theory is also undecidable.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The possible structure of intervals of this lattice is not very well understood.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The complement of the function which enumerates any maximal recursively enumerable set dominates every general recursive function.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] There exists maximal recursively enumerable set of Turing degree at most **0′**.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] For any two maximal recursively enumerable sets *A* and *B*, there exists an order automorphism of the lattice of recursively enumerable sets that maps *A* to *B*; this automorphism, however, may not always be computable.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] According to the Church–Turing thesis, any effectively calculable function is calculable by a Turing machine, and thus a set *S* is computably enumerable if and only if there is some algorithm which yields an enumeration of *S*.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] This cannot be taken as a formal definition, however, because the Church–Turing thesis is an informal conjecture rather than a formal axiom.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The definition of a computably enumerable set as the *domain* of a partial function, rather than the *range* of a total computable function, is common in contemporary texts.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] This choice is motivated by the fact that in generalized recursion theories, such as α-recursion theory, the definition corresponding to domains has been found to be more natural.
[src:recursion-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Other texts use the definition in terms of enumerations, which is equivalent for computably enumerable sets.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] In computer science and mathematical logic the **Turing degree** (named after Alan Turing) or **degree of unsolvability** of a set of natural numbers measures the level of algorithmic unsolvability of the set.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The concept of Turing degree is fundamental in computability theory, where sets of natural numbers are often regarded as decision problems.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The Turing degree of a set is a measure of how difficult it is to solve the decision problem associated with the set, that is, to determine whether an arbitrary number is in the given set.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Two sets are **Turing equivalent** if they have the same level of unsolvability; each Turing degree is a collection of Turing equivalent sets, so that two sets are in different Turing degrees exactly when they are not Turing equivalent.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] It is in this sense that the Turing degree of a set corresponds to its level of algorithmic unsolvability.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The Turing degrees were introduced by Post (1944) and many fundamental results were established by Kleene & Post (1954).
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The Turing degrees have been an area of intense research since then.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Many proofs in the area make use of a proof technique known as the **priority method**.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] For the rest of this article, the word *set* will refer to a set of natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] A set *X* is said to be **Turing reducible** to a set *Y* if there is an oracle Turing machine that decides membership in *X* when given an oracle for membership in *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The notation *X* ≤T *Y* indicates that *X* is Turing reducible to *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Two sets *X* and *Y* are defined to be **Turing equivalent** if *X* is Turing reducible to *Y* and *Y* is Turing reducible to *X*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The notation *X* ≡T *Y* indicates that *X* and *Y* are Turing equivalent.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] A **Turing degree** is an equivalence class of the relation ≡T.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The notation [*X*] denotes the equivalence class containing a set *X*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The entire collection of Turing degrees is denoted ${\mathcal {D}}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The Turing degrees have a partial order ≤ defined so that [*X*] ≤ [*Y*] if and only if *X* ≤T *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] There is a unique Turing degree containing all the computable sets, and this degree is less than every other degree.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] It is denoted **0** (zero) because it is the least element of the poset ${\mathcal {D}}$ .
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] (It is common to use boldface notation for Turing degrees, in order to distinguish them from sets.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The Turing degree of *X* ⊕ *Y* is the least upper bound of the degrees of *X* and *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Thus ${\mathcal {D}}$ is a join-semilattice.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The least upper bound of degrees **a** and **b** is denoted **a** ∪ **b**.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] It is known that ${\mathcal {D}}$ is not a lattice, as there are pairs of degrees with no greatest lower bound.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] For any set *X* the notation *X*′ denotes the set of indices of oracle machines that halt (when given their index as input) when using *X* as an oracle.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The set *X*′ is called the **Turing jump** of *X*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The Turing jump of a degree [*X*] is defined to be the degree [*X*′]; this is a valid definition because *X*′ ≡T *Y*′ whenever *X* ≡T *Y*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] A key example is **0**′, the degree of the halting problem.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] A great deal of research has been conducted into the structure of the Turing degrees.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The following survey lists only some of the many known results.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] One general conclusion that can be drawn from the research is that the structure of the Turing degrees is extremely complicated.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] A degree is called *recursively enumerable* (r.e.) or *computably enumerable* (c.e.) if it contains a recursively enumerable set.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Every r.e. degree is below **0**′, but not every degree below **0**′ is r.e..
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] However, a set A is many-one reducible to **0**′ if and only if A is r.e..
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Additionally, there is Shoenfield's limit lemma, a set *A* satisfies $[A]\leq _{T}\emptyset '$ if and only if there is a "recursive approximation" to its characteristic function: a function *g* such that for sufficiently large *s*, $g(s)=\chi _{A}(s)$ .
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Turing degrees and asked whether there is any r.e. degree strictly between **0** and **0**′.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The problem of constructing such a degree (or showing that none exist) became known as **Post's problem**.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] This problem was solved independently by Friedberg and Muchnik in the 1950s, who showed that these intermediate r.e. degrees do exist (Friedberg–Muchnik theorem).
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Their proofs each developed the same new method for constructing r.e. degrees, which came to be known as the **priority method**.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The priority method is now the main technique for establishing results about r.e. sets.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The idea of the priority method for constructing an r.e. set *X* is to list a countable sequence of *requirements* that *X* must satisfy.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] These requirements are put into a *priority ordering*, which is an explicit bijection of the requirements and the natural numbers.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The proof proceeds inductively with one stage for each natural number; these stages can be thought of as steps of time during which the set *X* is enumerated.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] At each stage, numbers may be put into *X* or forever (if not injured) prevented from entering *X* in an attempt to *satisfy* requirements (that is, force them to hold once all of *X* has been enumerated).
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Sometimes, a number can be enumerated into *X* to satisfy one requirement but doing this would cause a previously satisfied requirement to become unsatisfied (that is, to be *injured*).
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The priority order on requirements is used to determine which requirement to satisfy in this case.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] The informal idea is that if a requirement is injured then it will eventually stop being injured after all higher priority requirements have stopped being injured, although not every priority argument has this property.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] An argument must be made that the overall set *X* is r.e. and satisfies all the requirements.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Priority arguments can be used to prove many facts about r.e. sets; the requirements used and the manner in which they are satisfied must be carefully chosen to produce the required result.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] For example, a simple (and hence noncomputable r.e.) low *X* (low means *X*′=0′) can be constructed in infinitely many stages as follows.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] At the start of stage *n*, let *T**n* be the output (binary) tape, identified with the set of cell indices where we placed 1 so far (so *X*=∪*n* *T**n*; *T*0=∅); and let *P**n*(*m*) be the priority for not outputting 1 at location *m*; *P*0(*m*)=∞.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] At stage *n*, if possible (otherwise do nothing in the stage), pick the least *i*<*n* such that ∀*m* *P**n*(*m*)≠*i* and Turing machine *i* halts in <*n* steps on some input *S*⊇*T**n* with ∀*m*∈*S*\*T**n* *P**n*(*m*)≥*i*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Choose any such (finite) *S*, set *T**n*+1=*S*, and for every cell *m* visited by machine *i* on *S*, set *P**n*+1(*m*) = min(*i*, *P**n*(*m*)), and set all priorities >*i* to ∞, and then set one priority ∞ cell (any will do) not in *S* to priority *i*.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] Essentially, we make machine *i* halt if we can do so without upsetting priorities <*i*, and then set priorities to prevent machines >*i* from disrupting the halt; all priorities are eventually constant.
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] To see that *X* is low, machine *i* halts on *X* if and only if it halts in <*n* steps on some *T**n* such that machines <*i* that halt on *X* do so <*n*−*i* steps (by recursion, this is uniformly computable from 0′).
[src:recursion-theory/turing-degree] *X* is noncomputable since otherwise a Turing machine could halt on *Y* if and only if *Y*\*X* is nonempty, contradicting the construction since *X* excludes some priority *i* cells for arbitrarily large *i*; and *X* is simple because for each *i* the number of priority *i* cells is finite.
